\par\plain {\f0\fs22\b0\i0\cb5\highlight5 25.  Miracles are part of an interlocking chain of forgiveness which, when completed, is the Atonement. This process works all the time and in all the dimensions of time.}
\par\plain \f0\fs22\b0\i0\cb5\highlight5
\par\plain {\f0\fs22\b0\i0\cb5\highlight5 I am in charge of the process of Atonement, which I undertook to begin. When you offer a miracle unto any of my brothers, you do it unto yourself and me. The reason you come before me is that I do not need miracles for my own Atonement, but I stand at the end in case you fail temporarily. The purpose of my part in the Atonement is the canceling out of all lacks of love which men could not otherwise correct. The word "sin" should be changed to "lack of love" because "sin" is a man-made word with threat connotations which he made up himself. No real threat is involved anywhere. Nothing is gained by frightening yourselves, and it is very destructive to do so.}
\par\plain \f0\fs22\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs22\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs22\b0\i0 The UB uses our limited language and some UB authors express frustration with the limitations of our language. They describe sin in great detail. But here in lies the paradox. Spirit beings say the material world is almost entirely unreal to them. If they consider the material world unreal, what do you think their attitude towards sin is? Does God recognize sin? The UB says he has already forgiven us even before we ask. Jesus is telling us the eternal view of sin. He thinks of it as a lack of love, and our only response is to fill it. This attitude takes judgement out of the picture. The only response is to fill the lack with love. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs22\b0\i0 What is the internal language of a human mind if he is a fusion candidate? Should we try to understand Gods point of view? Is it even our job to judge guilt or innocence? The CIM tells us no. Was this how Jesus transcended our world? }
